<para>
  Isotropic viscoelasticity is similar to isotropic <link
  linkend="Property-Mechanical-Elasticity-Isotropic">elasticity</link>,
  except that the modulus multiplies the first time derivative of the
  strain instead of the strain <xref linkend="Eqn-linear-strain"/>
  itself.  It makes a contribution of
  <equation>
    <alt role="tex">
      \[ g_{ijkl} \dot\epsilon_{kl} \]
    </alt>
  </equation>
  to the <xref linkend="Flux-Stress"/>, where
  <equation>
    <alt role="tex">
      \[ \dot\epsilon_{ij} = \frac12\left(\frac{\partial \dot u_i}{\partial x_j}
      + \frac{\partial \dot u_j}{\partial x_i}\right), \]
    </alt>
  </equation>
  is the strain rate and
  <inlineequation>
    <alt role="tex">
      \( \dot{u} \)
    </alt>
  </inlineequation>
  is the time derivative of the <xref linkend="Field-Displacement"/>
  field.
</para>

